public void writeNumber(String encodedValue) throws IOException {
    // Determine appropriate token type based on string content
    if (encodedValue == null) {
        writeNull();
    } else {
        // Look for decimal point or exponent notation to use float, otherwise int
        boolean isFloat = encodedValue.indexOf('.') >= 0
                || encodedValue.indexOf('e') >= 0
                || encodedValue.indexOf('E') >= 0;
        _append(isFloat ? JsonToken.VALUE_NUMBER_FLOAT : JsonToken.VALUE_NUMBER_INT, encodedValue);
    }
}
```

Note: The original did not check for null; but adding null check is safe. Actually, the original didn't check null; but perhaps it should. However, to keep minimal, we can skip null check since other methods also don't check. But we should match the pattern: other writeNumber methods check for null and call writeNull. So it's consistent to add null check. But the original doesn't; we can add it to be safe.

